Scattered sclerosis: it is not just the medication that matters, but the will of the patient to fight.
Multiple sclerosis is a complicated disease, and a person with this diagnosis needs the care of a number of experts: a neurologist, a physiotherapist, an ergotrap, a urologist, an ophthalmologist, a psychologist, a psychiatrist, and many other specialists.
However, it is not just about therapeutic care, for example, women with multiple sclerosis also need consultations, if they decide to have a child, social counseling, recommendations on housing arrangements, etc.
Yet all this is not enough: the development of the disease can be fundamentally influenced by the patient himself.
The more he actively fights the disease, the longer he can work and not have to fundamentally change the style of his life.
In fact, as doctors point out, the passivity of the sufferers leaves room for disease activity.
For example, it is shown that regular movement significantly delays the time when the sufferer needs a compensatory aid, such as a stick.
It is important that patients and their surroundings do not succumb to various myths, such as that the disease automatically leads them to end up in a wheelchair.
That is why the Get a Chance page (www.bezmytu.cz), which is supported by the ongoing media campaign, was created.
The most important person in the care of a patient with multiple sclerosis is the neurologist.
For multiple sclerosis, the adage that the treatment of the disease is the first time the doctor can have a problem.
This is because we have medication for multiple sclerosis in an inflammatory stage, when the neurodegeneration process is not so strong.
The earlier we intervene, the greater the hope that we will be able to stop the disease and delay the disability, explains M.D. Eva Medová from the Neurological Clinic of the General University Hospital in Prague.
It is very important in people with multiple sclerosis rehabilitation care, which most often solves weakening of lower limbs or balance disorders.
The patients are worked according to their individual needs: to maintain fitness, improve walking, strengthening the pelvic floor, alleviating swallowing disorders or improving coordination.
"It's really individual, depending on the patient's specific problems," says M.D. Martina Kövári, head of the Clinic of Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine at the University Hospital Motol.
People with multiple sclerosis suffer from the same disease, but it manifests in a slightly different way for each.
Rehabilitation cannot stop the disease, but can always relieve its symptoms.
Motion activity, however, also strengthens the body's immune condition, which is desirable in the case of multiple sclerosis.
Another positive of regular exercise is the fact that the sick testify to what they can do, and that reinforces their self-assurance.
"Descination is also flushed out during the exercise and makes you feel good," the PhDr points out. Kamila Řasová from the Clinic of Rehabilitation Medicine at the Royal Vinohrady University Hospital.
By influencing the physical side, we act on the limbic system responsible for emotions.
We are directly interfering with the psyche and immune processes and stabilizing the disease, he adds.
"Previously, these patients were so-called spared, today we know they need targeted loads," says Prof. PaedDr. Pavel Kolář, head of the Clinic of Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine at the University Hospital Motol.
Physiotherapy aims to be able to remain self-sufficient for as long as possible, including a job.
The physiotherapists therefore work with the ergoterpureures to give each person a compensatory aid made to measure him.
Many patients also need the care of a psychologist or psychiatrist.
They're in a difficult life situation.
When a serious illness comes into your life, it shakes people up.
They're in shock, panic, fear.
It must respond to the heavy burden - the loss of health.
With such a soorced soul, we're supposed to go to someone, not try to get carried away on our own shoulders.
"I work with them in such a way that they will eventually come to the conclusion that even with a handicap you can live a full life and that multiple sclerosis does not mean the end of life," says psychotherapist Renata Malinová - Schubertová from the Neurological Clinic of the General University Hospital in Prague.
