The speed on the motorways will remain the same.
Acceleration to 150 km/h was rejected by the House.
On selected sections of motorways it will not be possible to increase the maximum speed allowed to up to 150 km/h under favourable conditions.
The House decided to do so on Tuesday when it agreed to the Senate amendment, which rejected the increase in speed.
The amendment to the Road Act will now head to the President.
President Miloš Zeman said at the end of April that he would veto the law allowing the 150-kilometre speed.
Transport Minister Dan Ťok (for ANO) was also against the increase, according to which the Czech motorway network is not yet built for such speed.
Speaking to MPs on Tuesday, Ťok supported the Senate's version of the bill.
The approved amendment will now allow, in line with the original government proposal, to increase the speed from 90 to 110 kilometres per hour on selected first-class roads, especially four-lane roads.
The House first extended this option to highways, which could be driven at speeds of up to 150 km/h on selected sections, but the Senate refused.
Members have now agreed to his proposal.
The senators, with the agreement of the Minister of Transport, also removed from the amendment the authorization of the traffic police to have the last word in adjusting the local roads handled by the municipalities.
The Senate version, which the House approved, also envisages that the sewerage, water supply or public lighting cables could be stored lengthwise under the road surface.
The municipalities would thus save on the purchase of the land.
Municipalities should also be required to take care of the road vegetation along local roads, regardless of the owner of the property in question.
The amendment is also intended to help improve road protection and make it easier for municipalities to deal with towed vehicles to which the owners do not subscribe.
Newly, municipalities could sell towed vehicles that their owners will not claim within the six-month period after the towing notification.
Municipalities will be able to exclude transit freight traffic through their territory on second and third-class roads under threat of a fine for freight forwarding firms.
The amendment also cancels the possibility to introduce electronic motorway vignettes instead of the existing paper ones, which will be used after 1 January next year.
According to the government, this will save money for the introduction of an electronic system.
